        " <p><strong>Salary 50,000 - 65,000 GBP per year </strong></p><br><p><strong>Requirements:</strong></p><p>- - Undergraduate degree in a relevant discipline e.g. Computer Science, Software Engineering etc, or equivalent professional experience. <br>- Professional software development (backend) using Java and/or TypeScript <br>- Use of DevOps: source control, build automation, QA, deployment and monitoring. Experience of Git, Linux and Docker<br>- Design, documentation, testing and maintenance of complex software systems <br>- Experience of PostgreSQL or similar RDBMS</p><br><br><p><strong>Responsibilities:</strong></p><p>- In this role you’ll be developing Minder, an innovative healthcare technology platform supporting the care of people affected by dementia and other conditions. The Minder software team is part of a larger group of clinical researchers, data scientists, healthcare professionals and designers who work collaboratively on the project. The job will involve writing code in Java and/or TypeScript and developing the cloud infrastructure on which it runs. You can expect have an influential role in the ongoing implementation and deployment of the platform, which is being rolled out in a growing number of care settings. <br><br>The software team uses an agile development methodology following software engineering best practices for version control, build automation and continuous delivery. We develop user interfaces and backend services in addition to infrastructure for software deployment, data management and execution of machine learning models. By contributing to this mission you will become a valued member of a highly capable team based at a world class research institution that provides it members with a broad range of employee benefits, including extensive opportunities for personal development. <br><br>- Develop and maintain secure, scalable and robust backend services <br>- Provision and support cloud-native infrastructure <br>- Deploy and manage systems for data management and analysis <br>- Work with designers and end-users to develop technical specifications <br>- Document code and establish relevant QA protocols <br>- Contribute to efforts to obtain medical device certification for the platform <br>- Keep up to date with technology trends and industry standards, in particular those related to healthcare and medical devices <br>- Work closely with other members of the Centre to promote understanding of the software team’s work, resolve support requests, explain technical challenges, establish unmet needs and successfully deliver projects <br>- Assist in the creation of an environment where all team members can fully contribute and voice their questions, opinions or concerns </p><br><br><p><strong>Technologies:</strong></p><p>- Java<br>- TypeScript<br>- PostgreSQL<br>- Kubernetes<br>- Kubeflow<br>- GitLab<br>- Docker<br>- Linux<br>- Azure<br>- NATS<br>- Spring Boot<br>- Spring<br>- Angular<br>- Backend</p><br><p>More: </p>This position is within the UK DRI Care Research and Technology Centre at Imperial College London, which has been established to address a medical research area of highest importance and future impact as one of seven new national centres of excellence embedded in major UK universities. Together the centres will transform the diagnosis, treatment, and care of people with dementia. The MRC, alongside charity partners Alzheimer's Society and Alzheimer's Research UK, have invested £250m in fulfilment of the ambition identified in the Prime Minister's 2020 Challenge on Dementia. ",
